Introduction

Last week we were introduced to some of the workhorse geoprocessing functions of GIS. This week we continue exploring geoprocessing and start to cover one of the most important analytic tools in the spatial analyst’s toolbox- the spatial join. For this walk through we’ll be using sf, tmap and the tidyverse.

Merge

I demonstrated a version of this last week. Merge is a way to combine varied layers together. A common usage is if you have some particularly large or complex geography so you break it into multiple pieces and then wish to stitch it back together. Merge is primarily a geometric operation, but it brings over all attributes. This can mean our final table can be fairly weird looking if you do not have consistent column names. Note! This is NOT a join in a formal sense. We are not associating any set of attributes from one layer with another. We are literally just sticking these geographies together.

In R, we can run the equivalent of a merge using the bind_rows() function from dplyr. Base-R also has an rbind() function that does the same thing, but sf has optimized itself to the dplyr function. Let’s take a look. I have already loaded my necessary packages. So, let’s take another look inside the demonstrating tools geodatabase that Prof. O’Neill set up for us.

if(!require(pacman)){install.packages("pacman"); library(pacman)}

So, in the video, Prof. O’Neill takes the three neighborhood shapefiles and merges them together into one new multipolygon feature. We will do the same now using bind_rows(). Let’s take a look. In order to save some space I am going to save the path to the geodatabase in a variable and then use that in my st_read() calls to save space. This is a good thing to do with any kind of repeated variable in your projects. It saves time, it protects yourself from typos and makes it easier to troubleshoot.

gdb_path <- "Oct12_Spatial_Join_Data/Oct5_DemonstratingTools.gdb"

hood1 <- st_read(dsn = gdb_path, layer = "Neighborhoods_One_1", quiet = TRUE)
hood2 <- st_read(dsn = gdb_path, layer = "Neighborhoods_Two_1", quiet = TRUE)
hood3 <- st_read(dsn = gdb_path, layer = "Neighborhoods_Three_1", quiet = TRUE)

If you’d like, take a moment to peruse these three layers. Note, they have a different number of rows, but the same number of columns and the columns share column names except for N*Field columns. Let’s bind/merge them together and see what we have.The bind should go smoothly and you should note that we have two additional columns in our table corresponding to our unique columns in the tables! Remember, the computer is naive and so it will merge these layers for you, but will try not to assume that differently labeled columns mean the same thing. Conversely, you could have columns of the same name that mean different things that could get merged. So we want to remain careful. Now, let’s see what this looks like.

hood_merge <- bind_rows(hood1, hood2, hood3)

Feature Conversions

Feature to Point st_centroid()

In the first example Prof. O’Neill demonstrates how one can get the centroid of a polygon using the “Feature to Point” tool. We can duplicate this operation using the st_centroid() function from sf. I won’t cover many of the sub-arguments of the function as they refer to a wider array of functions of which st_centroid() is merely one. Check the documentation for more details, if curious.

Note that st_centroid() is a geometric operation and carries over all of the table attributes of our object. This can be very useful for us in certain data processing workflows.

hood_centroids <- st_centroid(hood_merge)
## Warning in st_centroid.sf(hood_merge): st_centroid assumes attributes are
## constant over geometries of x
hood_centroid_tmap <- tm_shape(hood_merge) +
  tm_fill(col = "dodgerblue4") +
  tm_borders(col = "gray4") +
tm_shape(hood_centroids) +
  tm_dots(col = "magenta")

hood_centroid_tmap %>% 
  tmap_leaflet() %>% 
  leaflet::addLayersControl(overlayGroups = c("hood_merge", "hood_centroids"), position = "topright")

Neighborhood Centroids

Minimum Bounding Polygon and st_convex_hull

Prof. O’Neill next demonstrates how to get the convex hull from a set of Points. The convex hull, in our usages in GIS, is the minimal polygon necessary to encompass a set of points. There are many other ways to get at minimal bounding polygons such as circles or rectangles, but the convex hull is special for its minimization. The demo image is taken from Wikipedia.

The Convex Hull

sf has a function for this with st_convex_hull(). But, remember how ArcPro abstracts a lot of the middle steps for us? We have that same situation here. st_convex_hull() will generally try to respect groupings in your data and will search for columns that may have any kind of identifying information. In this case, the random points layer has two groups in CID. As such, the function will return a convex hull appropriate to each group. Let’s model this out a bit to get some clarity.

First, let’s just get a single polygon for the convex hull of all points. We can combine our geometries using st_combine(), get the convex hull of this now unified set of points and go from there.

rand_pts <- st_read(dsn = gdb_path, layer = "RandomPoints", quiet = TRUE)

rand_pts_hull <- rand_pts %>% 
  summarise(st_combine(x = Shape)) %>% 
  st_convex_hull()

hull1 <-  tm_shape(rand_pts) +
  tm_dots(col = "dodgerblue4") +
tm_shape(rand_pts_hull) +
  tm_fill(col = "magenta", alpha = .3)

hull1 %>% 
  tmap_leaflet() %>% 
  leaflet::addLayersControl(position = "topright")

Singular Convex Hull

Now, let’s group on the CID column and go from there. For simplicity’s sake, let’s transform the CID column in a categorical variable first, then group, summarise and get our respective convex hulls.The important steps here are the summarise and combine steps to tell the convex hull function explicitly which geometries to operate on so we can get a neat polygon. Again, this is lower level functionality than what ArcPro offers us with its tool, but I hope you can see how this could be useful in setting up your varied workflows.

rand_pts <- rand_pts %>% 
  mutate(CID = as.character(CID))

rand_pts_hull <- rand_pts %>% 
  group_by(CID) %>% 
  summarise(st_combine(x = Shape)) %>% 
  st_convex_hull()

hull2 <-  tm_shape(rand_pts) +
  tm_dots(col = "CID") +
tm_shape(rand_pts_hull) +
  tm_fill(col = "CID", alpha = .3)

hull2 %>% 
  tmap_leaflet() %>% 
  leaflet::addLayersControl(position = "topright")

Convex Hull by Group

In order to get something like a minimum bounding circle you could turn to the lwgeom package in R. lwgeom stands for “light weigth geometry library” and has an even greater array of geometric functions than is found even in sf. I won’t delve into it here out of respect for time, but check it out if you’re curious.

Dissolve

This was a tool we acquainted ourselves with last week in ArcPro with our running lab. Dissolve allows us to combine geometries together based upon some attribute. In this sense, dissolve is often used to simplify our dataset by removing extraneous attribute data and giving us a simpler set of polygons. In this sense, it is a summary operation. We select some kind of grouping criteria and then summarise from there. What does this sound like?

Let’s take a look. We will first take a look at the redlining zones layer and get a count of the zone ratings. What would be the dplyr approach for getting a count of rows by the condition score?

redlining_zones <- st_read(dsn = gdb_path, layer = "Redlining_Zones_to_Dissolve", quiet = TRUE)

Tally of Condition Scores

Condition n
Best 8
Declining 10
Hazardous 8
Still Desirable 14

So, our a-spatial summary operation took us from 40 rows down to four. This, functionally, is what dissolve does for us also, but with our geometries. Let’s take a look at this spatially using just our dplyr syntax.

redline_dissolve <- redlining_zones %>% 
  group_by(Condition) %>% 
  summarise() %>% 
  st_make_valid()

redline_dissolve_tmap <- tm_shape(redline_dissolve) +
    tm_fill(col = "Condition") +
  tm_shape(redlining_zones) +
  tm_fill(col = "Condition") +
  tmap_options(check.and.fix = TRUE)

redline_dissolve_tmap %>% 
  tmap_leaflet() %>% 
  leaflet::addLayersControl(overlayGroups = c("redlining_zones", "redline_dissolve"), position = "topright")

Dissolve by Condition Score

Understanding that dissolve here is acting similarly to our group_by and summarise calls, how would we do the operation Prof. O’Neill shows in this video with the roads? The ability for sf to play so well with dplyr in this kind of way is a real testament to the development teams and shows the strength of these tightly coupled packages.

Spatial Joins

Now we get to the good stuff. Spatial joins are a major part of what makes spatial analysis special (remember, spatial isn’t special…unit it is). Just as with table joins, we are associating the attributes of two different objects based upon their spatial relationship as opposed to have some set of shared variables that is already present in their attribute tables.

Let’s jump right in. Let’s join the neighborhood information to the crime data Prof. O’Neill presents for us. The main function here is st_join(), the general function for spatial joins in sf. Now, make note of the join = argument. That allows us to define the geometric relationship we want to join on. The default relationship is that of an intersection, but, in this case, I decided on st_within because we are dealing with points in polygons. But do note that for something like this the default will work just as well.Now, this particular use of st_join() joins all of the information from our neighborhood layer to the crime points. If all we wanted was the neighborhood name, how might we go about only joining the neighborhood name?

crimes <- st_read(dsn = gdb_path, layer = "Crimes_in_2014", quiet = TRUE)
hoods <- st_read(dsn = gdb_path, layer = "Neighborhhoods", quiet = TRUE)

crimes_w_hoods <- st_join(crimes, hoods, join = st_within)

Nearest Neighbor Spatial Join

Prof. O’Neill demonstrates a pretty cool example using nearest neighbor as part of a spatial join operation. How might we do this in R? Remember the nngeo package? Well, st_join() will take the st_nn() function from nngeo in its argument! So, let’s bring in the places to live and farmers markets and see this in action very quickly.

First, remember to bring in nngeo, then let’s follow our workflow. Now, we want our living places layer to have the information of the nearest farmers’ market. But first, we need to convert our units because nngeo didn’t like the US Feet.

library(nngeo)

farmers <- st_read(dsn = gdb_path, layer = "Farmers_Market", quiet = TRUE) %>% 
  st_transform(crs = 3364)

living_places <- st_read(gdb_path, layer = "Places_You_May_Live", quiet = TRUE) %>% 
  st_transform(crs = 3364)

living_places <- st_join(living_places, farmers, join = st_nn, k = 1)

Check that new living places layer to see if the join was successful. You should now have a living_places layer with 25 columns!

We’ve gone over merge, feature conversion and spatial joins in these past videos. Combined with our other foundational geoprocessing tools you are now knowledgeable in the tools necessary to do a large bulk of GIS analysis work. The ability to modify geometries, tabular attributes and their combinations is the essence of GIS work. How do we glean meaning, knowledge or information from a set of objects in space?
